Interpol has issued an international warrant for the arrest of two main suspects behind an ivory syndicate operating in the country.The agency released photographs of Samuel Jefwa and Nicholas Jefwa who had rented a house in Nyali, Mombasa.This was in connection to the Sh579 million ivory haul seized in Singapore in April 2015, in 40-foot containers disguised as tea consignments.The red alert notice indicated the brothers deal in wildlife trophies and are suspected to be hiding in South Sudan.Read: Interpol starts hunt for ivory smugglerAlso read: Sh579 million illegal ivory from Kenya seized in SingaporeInterpol said the Tanzanian nationals were the key suspects in the smuggling of Ivory from Tanzania to Kenya through the porous Lunga Lunga border.The agency said the trophies are then shipped through the Port of Mombasa. Anybody with information on their whereabouts should contact police or the Directorate of Criminal Investigations, read the notice.The two are well connected and allegedly colluded with custom and KPA officials to smuggle the ivory through the port.Three of their accomplices - Abdulrahman Sheikh, Sheikh Abdulrahman and Mahmoud Abdulrahman - were charged at Mombasa law courts with exporting 511 pieces of ivory to Thailand.Interpol's Nairobi Central Bureau senior officer Vitalis Okumu said they were working with the National Police Service in tracking down the suspects.The agency has dispatched a team to Nairobi to help fight illegal ivory trafficking, as part of efforts to arrest key individuals behind illegal ivory trade.The Star established that the unit was sharing information with Kenyan authorities and supporting intelligence analysis on ivory cartels in the region.Interpol was behind the arrest of Ivory Kingpin Feisal Mohammed who was later sentenced to 20 years in jail for trafficking ivory in July. He also ordered to pay a Sh20 million fine.His arrest came after the International Police Organisation put his name on a list of most wanted suspects linked to crimes against the environment.Read: Ivory kingpin Feisal Mohammed jailed 20 years, fined Sh20m